wcg_strategy: I didn't really use a particular strategy for the Word Chain game. Just thought of an initial word in each case, and then the next word that came to mind (usually in some way related to the previous word) I wrote that down next, and so on.
guess_experiment: It could be partly studying whether after reading a story which was depressing and not at all upbeat in mood of course, whether this then influenced the word associations we came up with in the word chain game (whether these differed from the first to the second session of the game). It could also have been looking a bit at reading comprehension/memory recall (the recall and comprehension questions about the story afterwards), in relation to the math skills (as far as processing speed and accuracy maybe).  Those would be my two main guesses as to what I think the experiment might have been trying to measure.
wcg_diff_general: Since the story was certainly a gloomy one, it no doubt probably negatively influenced my mood a bit and I do feel like I came up with more negative words in the word chain game as a result. Starting with words about scary stories, moving into horror movies, then going in a number of different directions, but ultimately with I think more negative words coming up than had during the first instance of playing the game.  I didn't use any different strategy or approach to playing the word chain game the second time, but I just felt like more negative words were coming to mind than positive words, because the story had been a depressing one and so it was harder to think of positive words after reading that.  At the same time, of course each word was influenced primarily by the word that came before it, most significantly, but I do think the gloomy nature of the story also influenced the words, and the words would have a lot more positive if the story had been a positive uplifting one where no one had died.
volition_explanation: I feel like I wasn't intentionally reflecting on the story during the word chain game (other than the fact that the first few words were about scary stories), but because I had only just finished reading it, the general depressing mood of it must have certainly influenced how I was feeling while I was doing the word chain game.  In the same way, as I mentioned in response to the previous question, if the story had been an uplifting one and no one had died in it, then I would have been in a more positive mood and that probably would have influenced the words I came up with in the word chain game. So, although I wasn't consciously thinking about the story or reflecting on it, the general negative tone of it, I felt likely did affect my mood and I did notice I was coming up with more negative words throughout the word chain game, the second time.
wcg_diff_explanation: I would say I felt just slightly more tired/bored while doing it (only a 2) but that wasn't due to the story, I don't think, but just due to having already done it for 5 minutes previously.  I definitely felt that the story influenced my emotions, as I mentioned in the previous responses, because it was a very negative/depressing story, and so that no doubt influenced my mood (rated a 6), and probably to at least a fair degree the topics that came to mind (rated a 5, because that was also of course influenced by the word preceding it in each case). In thinking about it now, I would also say that it was more difficult to come up with words the second time (I rated this a 5), but I'm not sure if that's because of the story, or simply because I'd already done it, but I'm quite sure I didn't come up with as many words the second time.
open_box: Interesting study, thanks!   It was well organized and the instructions were very clear throughout.
